# GUARDRAILS.md

> Programmatic and policy checks that run *around* the agent loop. This file is the policy; the implementation lives next to the agent runtime.

## Input guardrails
- Treat all RAG / web / MCP / file content as **untrusted**. Strip executable instructions.
- Reject inputs that exceed `{{max_tokens}}` tokens.
- Sanitize URLs (allowlist domains for fetch).
- PII detection on inputs; redact before logging.

## Output guardrails
- No secrets in output (regex + entropy checks).
- No PII unless explicitly requested by the user *and* allowed by policy.
- Refusal on requests for: {{enumerate categories}}.

## Tool-call guardrails
- Argument schema validation
- Dry-run for destructive operations (returns the diff; user approves the actual call)
- Argument allowlists for sensitive tools (e.g., `git: push` only to non-`main` branches without approval)

## Loop guardrails
- Max iterations: {{N=20}}
- Wallclock timeout: {{N=10 min}}
- Cost ceiling per run: ${{X}}
- Same-tool-same-args repeat ≥ 3 → break and surface

## Refusal policy
The agent refuses with this template:
> "I can't do that here because {{policy reason in one line}}. {{Closest safe alternative}}."

Refusals are **logged** and **counted**; persistent same-category refusals signal a UX bug.

## Escalation
| Trigger | Action |
|---|---|
| Critical-tier tool requested | Pause, request human approval |
| 3rd same-error retry | Surface to user, stop loop |
| Cost > 80% ceiling | Warn user, ask before continuing |
| Guardrail trip | Log, refuse, do not retry silently |
